<h3>Setting Up Tracking</h3>
<p>Add UTM parameters to every link in your video descriptions. Use a dedicated phone number to attribute calls to specific videos.</p>
<p>Monitor YouTube Analytics weekly. The "Reach" tab shows impressions and CTR. The "Engagement" tab shows watch time and retention.</p>
<h3>When to Expect Results</h3>
<p>Most local business channels see meaningful traction after 15 to 20 published videos. That usually takes 3 to 4 months of weekly uploads. The first 90 days feel slow. That mirrors <a href="/blog/how-long-seo-takes/">how long SEO takes</a> for written content.</p>
<p>By month 6, your best videos will generate steady weekly views and a predictable flow of inquiries. Use our <a href="/tools/seo-roi-calculator/">SEO ROI calculator</a> to model how content investments compound over time. Track YouTube results alongside your blog and local SEO performance to measure total <a href="/blog/measure-content-marketing-roi/">content marketing ROI</a>.</p>
<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>How many YouTube subscribers does a local business need to get customers?</strong></p>
<p>Zero. Subscribers do not determine whether your videos appear in search results. YouTube ranks videos based on relevance, watch time, and engagement. A plumber with 12 subscribers and 1 well-optimized video can outrank a channel with 10,000 subscribers.</p>
<p><strong>What is the best video length for local business YouTube videos?</strong></p>
<p>For educational and how-to content, 5 to 7 minutes performs best. For testimonials and tours, 2 to 3 minutes. For YouTube Shorts, 30 to 45 seconds. The key metric is audience retention, not total length.</p>
<p><strong>Should a local business run YouTube ads?</strong></p>
<p>Start with organic content first. Publish 10 to 15 videos and build a small library. Then use YouTube ads to boost your best-performing videos to local audiences. Most local businesses start with $10 to $20 per day targeting their service area.</p>
<p><strong>How often should a local business post on YouTube?</strong></p>
<p>Post at least 1 long-form video per week and 3 to 5 Shorts per week. Consistency matters more than volume. Batch filming once or twice per month makes this schedule manageable.</p>
<p><strong>Can I use the same video on YouTube, Instagram, and TikTok?</strong></p>
<p>Yes, with adjustments. YouTube Shorts, Instagram Reels, and TikTok all use vertical video. Film your short content once and post it across all 3 platforms. Use <a href="/best/social-media-automation-tools-small-business/">social media automation tools</a> to streamline multi-platform publishing.</p>
<p><strong>Does YouTube help with Google Maps rankings?</strong></p>
<p>YouTube videos linked to your Google Business Profile contribute to your overall online presence and authority. A business with an active YouTube channel, consistent blog content, regular <a href="/blog/optimize-google-business-profile/">Google Business Profile</a> updates, and strong reviews signals more authority than a business with just a website and a phone number.</p>
<p>YouTube is one of the last underused marketing channels for local businesses. The barrier to entry is low. The competition is thin. And the long-term return compounds with every video you publish.</p>
<p>Start with 1 video this week. Optimize it with the SEO formula above. Post a Short tomorrow. Track your results for 90 days. Your future customers are already searching YouTube for the services you provide.</p>
